I kind of agree with this. There's a fairly strong trope of (bored + immortal = depravity), which makes the ending a bit predictable. Of course, tropes are not inherently bad. 1733 also uses that trope, and it does it quite well.

Just as something to consider if you do want to change it: what if that's not a necessary outcome? You could do that in a few different ways. One is to simply not have the couple go into the flesh-rending, crime-committing direction. There are other aspects of  you touch, for example, on a shared body language being developed - this could become manifest in a full-fledged synchronicity of actions. Perhaps even a blurring of separate identities into a psuedo-hive-mind.

Another option would be to go through all the body horror stuff - then come out the other side, and go back to picnics in the park. Are there any interesting implications to a couple being able to do all those profoundly bizarre things and then go back to  experiences?







